02:31.758 --> 02:35.331
- _
- [school bell ringing]

02:36.720 --> 02:38.750
[Petra] The early reviews
are really good.

02:39.970 --> 02:41.469
[Noah] So I hear. I, uh,

02:41.470 --> 02:43.497
I try not to pay attention
to those things.

02:44.303 --> 02:46.844
I have to admit, I wasn't
such a fan of Descent,

02:46.845 --> 02:48.928
although, clearly, the
book didn't suffer

02:48.929 --> 02:51.177
from lack of fans, but...

02:51.178 --> 02:53.135
The Autobiography of Jack Hunter,

02:53.136 --> 02:55.075
it really moved me.

02:55.076 --> 02:59.302
It's a much more vulnerable,
mature piece of writing.

02:59.303 --> 03:00.980
Thanks.

03:00.981 --> 03:04.064
I mean, I... I wrote it in prison

03:04.065 --> 03:06.386
partly just to, uh, keep
myself from going insane.

03:06.387 --> 03:08.302
So just to get it published
at all is gratifying, and...

03:08.303 --> 03:11.509
You were in prison for killing
your brother-in-law, right?

03:12.389 --> 03:15.302
Uh, my, uh, ex-wife's
brother-in-law, yeah.

03:15.989 --> 03:17.669
But there's plenty of stuff
out there about that.

03:17.670 --> 03:18.842
I-I really don't want to

03:18.843 --> 03:20.761
- make this about...
- No, no, no. It's just...

03:20.762 --> 03:22.094
ten years ago you were

03:22.095 --> 03:23.752
a public school teacher
living in Brooklyn,

03:23.753 --> 03:26.761
and then one summer, you wrote a novel

03:26.762 --> 03:28.427
that was an overnight sensation.

03:28.428 --> 03:31.761
You left your wife and family,
you married your mistress,

03:31.762 --> 03:34.052
you became suddenly famous and...

03:34.053 --> 03:35.719
I don't know, let's say you drank

03:35.720 --> 03:37.248
a little bit of your own Kool-Aid.

03:38.275 --> 03:40.260
You became increasingly arrogant,

03:40.261 --> 03:43.761
self-absorbed, reckless,
until one fateful night

03:43.762 --> 03:45.327
on the dark roads of Montauk,

03:45.328 --> 03:46.969
you hit someone and fled
the scene of the crime...

03:46.970 --> 03:48.917
I'm going somewhere with this.

03:48.918 --> 03:49.969
I hope so.

03:49.970 --> 03:53.302
You had an enormous fall from grace.

03:53.303 --> 03:55.508
You went to prison, you served time,

03:55.509 --> 03:58.133
you... lost everything.

03:59.034 --> 04:00.427
And now you're out,

04:00.428 --> 04:02.928
you've gone back to teaching
underprivileged kids,

04:02.929 --> 04:04.969
you have moved to be
closer to your family.

04:04.970 --> 04:06.966
You seem to be living a quiet life now.

04:08.415 --> 04:10.025
You've come full circle.

04:11.823 --> 04:14.552
So would you say that the redemption

04:14.553 --> 04:16.798
of Noah Solloway is complete?

04:18.762 --> 04:20.261
[chuckles softly]

04:22.613 --> 04:23.697
Um...

04:27.818 --> 04:30.387
Uh, y-you read the book, y-you tell me.

04:31.844 --> 04:34.010
That seems like a perfect place to stop.

04:36.220 --> 04:38.277
I'm really excited about this piece.

04:38.278 --> 04:40.590
People love a comeback story.

04:40.591 --> 04:41.969
When will they run it, do you know?

04:41.970 --> 04:44.469
Well, it's not up to me, but, um,

04:44.470 --> 04:46.930
they're hoping to time it with
the release of your movie.

04:46.931 --> 04:48.769
Your book is coming out
around then, too, isn't it?

04:48.770 --> 04:49.949
That's right.

04:49.950 --> 04:51.844
It's quite a year you're having.

04:51.845 --> 04:53.510
Oh, um, one more thing.

04:53.511 --> 04:54.785
Are you seeing anyone?

04:56.453 --> 04:58.527
Our readers will want to know.

05:00.484 --> 05:02.863
Uh... no.

05:02.864 --> 05:04.245
No, not at the moment.

05:04.246 --> 05:06.498
Really? That surprises me.

05:07.537 --> 05:08.844
Yeah, well, I guess that's, uh,

05:08.845 --> 05:10.678
that's one piece of the puzzle

05:10.679 --> 05:12.678
I haven't quite figured out yet.

05:13.585 --> 05:14.792
There's still time.

05:15.505 --> 05:18.179
Oh, I should probably turn this off.

05:18.845 --> 05:20.344
You still use those things?

05:20.345 --> 05:21.678
I thought young reporters these days

05:21.679 --> 05:22.886
just used their iPhone.

05:22.887 --> 05:24.427
Well, I'm not that young,

05:24.428 --> 05:26.672
and the batteries on these
things last longer.

05:26.673 --> 05:29.177
The last time I saw one,
I was interviewing

05:29.178 --> 05:31.135
a friend in Freshman Psych.

05:31.136 --> 05:33.120
Oh, you know, speaking of friends,

05:33.121 --> 05:34.987
could I call some of them?

05:34.988 --> 05:36.675
You know, to round out the picture?

05:36.676 --> 05:39.010
Who is Noah Solloway, the man?

05:39.011 --> 05:41.135
- Uh, sure. Of course.
- [door closes]

05:41.136 --> 05:42.678
[Joel] I can do that.

05:42.679 --> 05:46.594
I can... talk... for the article.

05:46.595 --> 05:48.094
You're Petra Ranes. I love your work.

05:48.095 --> 05:50.094
I-I read everything you write.

05:50.095 --> 05:51.969
[Petra] Oh, thanks. Uh, who are you?

05:51.970 --> 05:54.184
I'm the principal, actually.

05:54.185 --> 05:57.354
Of this, uh, school.

05:57.355 --> 05:58.844
But we're also friends.

05:58.845 --> 06:01.386
And I'm a novelist, too,
so we have that whole

06:01.387 --> 06:03.344
- simpatico thing going, and...
- You know what?

06:03.345 --> 06:04.761
I-I'll, uh, I'll think
of a couple of names

06:04.762 --> 06:06.094
- and get back to you.
- Great.

06:06.095 --> 06:07.386
Thank you for your time.

06:07.387 --> 06:08.665
Thank you.

06:16.787 --> 06:19.073
Vanity Fair?

06:19.074 --> 06:20.552
Wow.

06:20.553 --> 06:22.788
This is gonna be big for you.

06:23.720 --> 06:25.834
- We'll see.
- I mean, this is...

06:25.835 --> 06:28.302
top-tier literary recognition.

06:28.303 --> 06:30.094
That's rarified air.

06:30.095 --> 06:32.286
You want to go out? Celebrate tonight?

06:32.287 --> 06:34.135
Talk about our craft?

06:34.136 --> 06:35.594
Uh, no. I got to, um,

06:35.595 --> 06:37.344
I got to have dinner with my daughter,

06:37.345 --> 06:39.637
and then I'm gonna be on
set till-till late, so...

06:39.638 --> 06:41.135
"I'm gonna be on set."

06:41.136 --> 06:43.094
Jesus, man. Who are you?

06:43.095 --> 06:45.636
It's okay, I stay up
late. I'll call you.

06:45.637 --> 06:48.594
I mean, I got to buy a beer
for the man who has it all.

06:48.595 --> 06:50.219
Maybe.

06:50.220 --> 06:52.177
[indistinct chatter]

06:52.178 --> 06:54.345
[soft piano music playing]

07:01.317 --> 07:03.096
Is Colin coming,

07:03.097 --> 07:04.337
- or should we just order?
- Uh, no.

07:04.338 --> 07:06.344
He'll be here. He just...

07:06.345 --> 07:08.094
When he works, he can get carried away,

07:08.095 --> 07:09.876
lose track of time.

07:09.877 --> 07:12.380
I can't believe you're getting married.

07:12.381 --> 07:14.181
I know. Me either.

07:15.501 --> 07:16.719
You okay?

07:16.720 --> 07:18.255
Yeah, I'm fine.

07:19.506 --> 07:21.466
- How's work?
- Work's fine.

07:24.758 --> 07:26.029
Whit.

07:27.614 --> 07:29.135
Is something wrong?

07:29.136 --> 07:31.778
I don't want to pry,
but you seem kind of,

07:31.779 --> 07:33.761
- I don't know.
- I'm just tired, Dad.

07:33.762 --> 07:36.301
I-I have to be at the gallery
by seven every morning.

07:36.302 --> 07:38.552
We don't have air conditioning
'cause Andrea's too cheap.

07:38.553 --> 07:40.803
It's hot as hell and, you
know, I'm doing everything:

07:40.804 --> 07:43.719
I-I hang the art, I man the
phones, I keep the books.

07:43.720 --> 07:46.713
All she does is check her
Raya profile and freak out.

07:46.714 --> 07:48.219
What's a...? Never mind.

07:48.220 --> 07:49.704
So you don't like this job?

07:49.705 --> 07:52.052
I mean, it beats copy editing Art Forum.

07:52.053 --> 07:54.202
Well, maybe you could
find another gallery

07:54.203 --> 07:55.869
where the boss is a
little more reasonable.

07:55.870 --> 07:57.186
I can't quit. We need the money.

07:57.187 --> 07:59.813
Colin still can't work 'cause
of his visa situation, so...

07:59.814 --> 08:02.969
Well, would it help if
I gave you the money,

08:02.970 --> 08:04.844
- just to...
- Oh, no. Thanks, Dad.

08:04.845 --> 08:06.636
That's-that's not it. It's just that...

08:06.637 --> 08:08.344
like, when I come home
from a long day of work

08:08.345 --> 08:09.886
and I just want to, you know,

08:09.887 --> 08:11.511
have a glass of wine and
watch The Kardashians,

08:11.512 --> 08:13.929
I can't because Colin's
all over me to study.

08:13.930 --> 08:16.344
- Study?
- Yeah, for his immigration interview.

08:16.345 --> 08:18.135
You know, they put us in separate rooms,

08:18.136 --> 08:20.052
and if we don't get every
single question perfectly,

08:20.053 --> 08:21.386
Colin doesn't get his citizenship.

08:21.387 --> 08:23.595
Oh, hold on, hold on. Thank you.

08:25.011 --> 08:26.260
[chuckles]

08:26.261 --> 08:28.177
What?

08:29.017 --> 08:30.543
You remind me of your mother.

08:30.544 --> 08:32.094
Because I'm an alcoholic?

08:32.697 --> 08:33.943
No.

08:34.857 --> 08:36.679
'Cause you're so beautiful.

08:38.804 --> 08:40.169
Thanks.

08:41.379 --> 08:42.797
Whitney...

08:44.591 --> 08:47.340
this marriage thing, you don't
have to do it, you know.

08:47.928 --> 08:49.113
It seems rushed.

08:49.114 --> 08:51.511
Yeah, but actually, Dad, I
do, because if I don't,

08:51.512 --> 08:53.052
then Colin has to leave the country.

08:53.053 --> 08:54.601
Well, not forever, right?

08:54.602 --> 08:56.052
I mean, maybe that's for the best.

08:56.053 --> 08:58.052
He can go home, he can
establish himself there,

08:58.053 --> 08:59.923
and then apply for citizenship
on his own merit.

08:59.924 --> 09:02.010
What are you talking about? I'm
not gonna let him get deported.

09:02.011 --> 09:03.265
I-I love him.

09:03.266 --> 09:04.596
I just...

09:05.553 --> 09:07.926
I don't think it's supposed
to be this hard, Whitney.

09:08.553 --> 09:10.260
You are so young.

09:10.261 --> 09:12.358
It's too early to be this hard.

09:12.359 --> 09:14.344
I don't know if you
remember, Mr. Big Shot,

09:14.345 --> 09:16.135
but you were a struggling
artist once, too.

09:16.136 --> 09:17.856
Mom didn't leave you.

09:17.857 --> 09:20.428
I mean, you left her
20 years later, but...

09:23.704 --> 09:25.977
Whitney, I... I had a job.

09:26.937 --> 09:28.427
I was a teacher.

09:28.428 --> 09:30.427
I never let your mother support me.

09:30.428 --> 09:31.678
Look, I'm not saying

09:31.679 --> 09:32.886
- he's not a good guy...
- [Colin] Sorry.

09:32.887 --> 09:35.251
- Sorry, Mr. Solloway.
- Hi.

09:35.252 --> 09:38.024
- Whit. How you doing?
- Hi.

09:38.025 --> 09:40.101
I got a bit lost in the work. [sniffs]

09:40.848 --> 09:42.241
Have we ordered?

09:43.307 --> 09:45.094
No. Here.

09:45.095 --> 09:46.313
Here you go.

09:46.314 --> 09:47.887
Oh, thanks.

09:50.881 --> 09:52.421
Do they do vegan?

09:58.136 --> 09:59.762
[phone ringing]

10:04.387 --> 10:06.715
- Hi.
- [Janelle] Hi.

10:07.966 --> 10:09.551
Long time.

10:10.553 --> 10:13.804
Um... I know. At least a month, right?

10:15.268 --> 10:17.075
It's three, actually.

10:17.804 --> 10:19.550
Has it been three months? Wow.

10:19.551 --> 10:21.887
Time really does fly when you're busy.

10:24.621 --> 10:26.135
Why are you calling, Janelle?

10:26.136 --> 10:29.636
I feel badly about the way
things ended between us.

10:29.637 --> 10:31.302
You mean, when you disappeared

10:31.303 --> 10:33.469
after my ex-wife's boyfriend's funeral

10:33.470 --> 10:35.010
and then never returned my calls?

10:35.011 --> 10:37.443
Yes. I'd actually like to
explain some things in person.

10:37.444 --> 10:38.743
Are you free tonight?

10:38.744 --> 10:40.941
Uh... it'd have to be pretty late.

10:41.755 --> 10:43.323
I don't mind waiting up.

10:50.595 --> 10:52.177
[Sasha] What am I gonna do?

10:52.178 --> 10:54.534
I can't stop thinking about you.

10:54.535 --> 10:56.107
[Pru] I like you.

10:56.108 --> 10:57.874
I like everything about you.

10:57.875 --> 11:00.260
[Sasha] I could be
wanted in four states.

11:00.261 --> 11:02.803
- Helen.
- Shh!

11:02.804 --> 11:04.511
[Pru] I'll take my chances.

11:04.512 --> 11:07.095
[Sasha] We don't know
anything about each other.

11:09.787 --> 11:12.344
I am never gonna leave my wife.

11:13.294 --> 11:15.210
I don't expect you to.

11:15.211 --> 11:17.377
[Sasha] And she can never find out.

11:18.137 --> 11:19.427
[Pru] I understand.

11:19.428 --> 11:21.886
[Sasha] You still want to do this?

11:21.887 --> 11:23.345
[Pru] Yes.

11:27.553 --> 11:28.928
And cut.

11:28.929 --> 11:30.928
- [woman] All right.
- Wasn't that great?

11:30.929 --> 11:33.177
- [indistinct chatter]
- They're so great together.

11:33.178 --> 11:34.386
Wh-Why are you here?

11:34.387 --> 11:36.068
- You come... You looking for me?
- Oh...

11:36.069 --> 11:38.761
Oh, no. Uh, I might have a...

11:38.762 --> 11:41.474
sort of a work opportunity here.

11:41.475 --> 11:42.669
What? On the movie?

11:42.670 --> 11:45.802
No-no-no-no-no, just through
people connected with the movie.

11:45.803 --> 11:47.216
I don't want to say too much about it,

11:47.217 --> 11:48.450
in case it doesn't happen.

11:49.690 --> 11:51.878
How was dinner with,
uh, Colin and Whitney?

11:52.529 --> 11:53.845
It was fine.

11:55.462 --> 11:57.344
She looks kind of exhausted,
though, don't you think?

11:57.345 --> 11:59.386
I mean, burning the candle at both ends.

11:59.387 --> 12:00.887
Well, she's trying to climb the ladder.

12:01.845 --> 12:03.404
Hate seeing her like this.

12:03.405 --> 12:05.427
Actually, I think, for the
first time in her life,

12:05.428 --> 12:07.746
she's acting like an adult.

12:07.747 --> 12:09.445
But if you want to freak
out about something,

12:09.446 --> 12:10.546
you can freak out about the fact

12:10.547 --> 12:12.239
that she wants to get married
at my parents' house,

12:12.240 --> 12:13.904
and, uh, they're trying to sell it.

12:14.864 --> 12:16.386
Wait, your parents are selling?

12:16.387 --> 12:18.111
- That's what I hear.
- Why?

12:18.112 --> 12:19.678
I don't know. I can't
get a straight answer

12:19.679 --> 12:21.010
out of my mother. Like, my father made

12:21.011 --> 12:22.825
some bad business investments,

12:22.826 --> 12:24.511
which really doesn't sound like him.

12:24.512 --> 12:25.605
- So I'm...
- Helen.

12:25.606 --> 12:26.761
- I don't really know.
- Helen.

12:26.762 --> 12:27.969
About your father...

12:27.970 --> 12:29.753
[Sasha] Just the man I need to see.

12:29.754 --> 12:32.062
Noah Solloway, quick word?

12:32.063 --> 12:34.344
Sure. Yeah. Yeah. Sure.

12:34.345 --> 12:35.427
Walk with me.

12:35.428 --> 12:37.803
Sorry. Don't go anywhere.

12:37.804 --> 12:39.512
Uh, I'm here.

12:40.595 --> 12:42.762
[sighs]

12:46.261 --> 12:49.771
I just think we need to
make some decisions, Noah,

12:49.772 --> 12:52.147
about who this character really is.

12:52.148 --> 12:53.302
Okay.

12:53.303 --> 12:56.010
[exhales] In that last scene,

12:57.541 --> 12:58.761
Daniel tells Lana that

12:58.762 --> 13:01.135
he's never gonna leave his wife. Okay?

13:02.144 --> 13:03.677
Now, does he say that

13:04.430 --> 13:06.446
because he's a fundamentally good man

13:06.447 --> 13:08.903
who's trying to be honest about
what he has to give her?

13:08.904 --> 13:13.761
Or... does he say that as
some sort of manipulation,

13:13.762 --> 13:16.344
so that she will think
whatever happens next

13:16.345 --> 13:17.886
is actually her own fault?

13:17.887 --> 13:20.427
I mean... the first one.

13:20.428 --> 13:22.489
Because what I just did now,

13:22.490 --> 13:24.427
I shot it both ways so I
can decide in editing,

13:24.428 --> 13:25.844
but I'm not gonna shoot

13:25.845 --> 13:27.281
the whole fucking movie like that.

